\newpage\EMPHASIZE{Thinking of Objects}

You should think of a class as a rubber stamp for creating objects.

You should think of each object as a computational machine.

You can (and should) think of the ``stuff'' on the green band (the
\textit{m1}, \textit{m2}, \textit{print}) -- the \textit{public} things -- as
things that outsiders can access while the stuff on the inside (the
\textit{x\_}) -- the \textit{private} things -- are not available to
outsiders. By outsiders, I mean functions not in the class and methods
not in this class (i.e. methods of another class).


\newpage\EMPHASIZE{What is the Invoking Object}

What if a method must know the invoking object? Here's
such an example:

\begin{consolethree}[escapeinside=||]
class Int
{
public:
    ...
    Int max(const Int & c)
    {
        if (c.x_ > x_)
        {
            return c;
        }
        else
        {
            return ???;
        }
    }
private:
    int x_;
};
\end{consolethree}

\begin{consolethree}[escapeinside=||]
int main()
{
    Int a(100), b(1);
    Int c = a.max(b);
    return 0;
}
\end{consolethree}

For \textit{a.max(b)} we want to return \textit{a}. But what's the name of
\textit{a} in the code of \textit{max()}??? In general, what's the name of
the object making the call?

There is a secret parameter in every method. You do not pass this
parameter into the method. It's done for you automatically.

What is this secret parameter??? ...


\newpage\EMPHASIZE{The this Pointer}

Try the program below.

\begin{consolethree}[escapeinside=||]
// Int.h
#ifndef INT_H
#define INT_H

#include <iostream>

class Int
{
public:
    Int(int x) : x_(x) {}
    void print()
    {
        std::cout << this << x_ << "\n";
    }
private:
    int x_;
};

#endif
\end{consolethree}

\begin{consolethree}[escapeinside=||]
// main.cpp
#include <iostream>
#include "Int.h"

int main()
{
    Int i(42);
    std::cout << &i << "\n";
    i.print();
    Int j(0);
    std::cout << &j << "\n";
    j.print();
    return 0;
}
\end{consolethree}

When an object \textit{obj} invokes a method \textit{m}, a special pointer
\textit{this} is passed into \textit{m} automatically. The important thing
to remember is that:

\textit{this} points to \textit{obj}

If an object \textit{obj} has member variable \textit{x\_} and \textit{this}
is a pointer to \textit{obj}, then the following are the same:

\textit{obj.x\_} \hspace{1cm} \textit{(*this).x\_} \hspace{1cm} \textit{this->x\_}

This is the same notation used for pointers to \textit{struct} variables.
You should \textbf{\textit{not}} use \textit{(*this).x\_}. Write
\textit{this->x\_} instead.

(There is an exception. Static methods do not have the \textit{this}
secret parameter discussed here. We will talk about static methods
later.)

\textbf{WARNING:} \textit{*p.x} means \textit{*(p.x)} because \textit{.} has
higher precedence than \textit{*}. Make sure you try changing the
following

\begin{consolethree}[escapeinside=||]
class Int
{
public:
    ...
    void print()
    {
        std::cout << x_ << "\n";
    }
    ...
private:
    int x_;
};
\end{consolethree}

to this:

\begin{consolethree}[escapeinside=||]
class Int
{
public:
    ...
    void print()
    {
        std::cout << this->x_ << "\n";
    }
    ...
private:
    int x_;
};
\end{consolethree}

OK ... now to use \textit{this} ...


\newpage\EMPHASIZE{When do you use this?}

\textbf{Standard Practice:} Don't use \textit{this} in a method just to
access members or member functions. In other words, in a method

\begin{itemize}
\item \textit{this->x} should be \textit{x}
\item \textit{this->m()} should be \textit{m()}
\end{itemize}

For instance, this does work:

\begin{consolethree}[escapeinside=||]
...
class Date
{
public:
    ...
    int get_year()
    {
        return this->yyyy_;
    }
    void set_year(int y)
    {
        this->yyyy_ = y;
    }
    ...
    void add_m_y(int m, int d)
    {
        this->add_m(m);
        this->add_d(d);
    }
private:
    ...
};
\end{consolethree}

but \textbf{DON'T DO THAT!!!} Do this:

\begin{consolethree}[escapeinside=||]
...
class Date
{
public:
    ...
    int get_year()
    {
        return yyyy_;
    }
    void set_year(int y)
    {
        yyyy_ = y;
    }
    ...
    void add_m_y(int m, int d)
    {
        add_m(m);
        add_d(d);
    }
private:
    ...
};
\end{consolethree}

The pointer \textit{this} is used when it's used on its own either as
\textit{this} or \textit{*this}. In particular \textit{*this} can be used for
returning a copy of or a reference to the object making the method
invocation and \textit{this} can be used for address comparison
(you'll see this later when we need to compare address
values when we overload the assignment operator \textit{operator=}.)

(There are exceptions ... later. But the above two uses are good
enough.)


\newpage\EMPHASIZE{Returning a copy of *this}

\begin{consolethree}[escapeinside=||]
...
class Int
{
    ...
    Int max(const Int & c)
    {
        if (c.x_ > x_)
            return c;
        else
            return *this;
    }
    ...
private:
    int x_;
};
...
\end{consolethree}

And now you can try this:

\begin{consolethree}[escapeinside=||]
#include "Int.h"

int main()
{
    Int a(100), b(1);
    Int c = a.max(b); // a.max(b) should return an
                      // Int object with x_ value of
                      // 100
    c.print();
    return 0;
}
\end{consolethree}

Of course, this is better:

\begin{consolethree}[escapeinside=||]
...
class Int
{
public:
    ...
    Int max(const Int & c)
    {
        return (c.x_ > x_ ? c : *this);
    }
    ...
private:
    int x_;
};
...
\end{consolethree}

Get it? In this case, we are returning a copy of the \textit{Int} object
that \textit{this} points to, i.e., the object invoking the method.

Notice however that you can also do this:

\begin{consolethree}[escapeinside=||]
...
class Int
{
    ...
    Int & max(const Int & c)
    {
        return (c.x_ > x_ ? c : *this);
    }
    ...
private:
    int x_;
};
...
\end{consolethree}

In this case, a \textbf{reference is returned}.

Why is this important? Look at this code:

\begin{consolethree}[escapeinside=||]
#include "Int.h"

int main()
{
    Int a(100), b(1);
    Int c = a.max(b);
    c.print();
    return 0;
}
\end{consolethree}

This means if the return of \textit{Int::max()} is an \textit{Int} and not
an \textit{Int \&}

\begin{consolethree}[escapeinside=||]
...
class Int
{
public:
    ...
    Int max(const Int & c)
    {
        ...
    }
    ...
};
...
\end{consolethree}

then an \textit{Int} value is returned (it has the same values as \textit{a}
or \textit{b}). This \textit{Int} value is used for the invocation of the
\textit{Int} copy constructor to initialize \textit{c}.

Make sure you read the last two sentences again (and again and again).

However if a reference is returned:

\begin{consolethree}[escapeinside=||]
...
class Int
{
public:
    ...
    Int & max(const Int & c)
    {
        ...
    }
    ...
};
...
\end{consolethree}

then back in \textit{main()}, on returning from \textit{Int::max()}, a reference to a or to b is used by
the copy constructor to initialize \textit{c}. There's no
extra \textit{Int} object created by \textit{Int::max()} that is used to
initialize \textit{c}.

Let me repeat again: when you return \textit{Int} (not \textit{Int \&}), a
copy of the object to be returned is made (by using the copy
constructor).

Whereas if you return \textit{Int \&}, no \textit{Int} object is created.
The copy constructor used to create \textit{c} will simply reference
\textit{a} or \textit{b}.


\newpage\EMPHASIZE{Returning references}

In the previous section, I have shown you an example of returning a
reference.

Certain methods and operators update the values of the variables or
objects and return the values of the variables or objects. Run this:

\begin{consolethree}[escapeinside=||]
int x = 5;
x++;
std::cout << x << std::endl;
int y = x++;
std::cout << x << ',' << y << std::endl;
y = (x += 5);
std::cout << x << ',' << y << std::endl;
(x += 5) += 5;
std::cout << x << std::endl;
\end{consolethree}

Don't overdo this! Why? Because

\begin{consolethree}[escapeinside=||]
y = (x += 5);
\end{consolethree}

does too many things. A function/method/operator should do
\textbf{\textit{one}} thing to avoid confusion. This is clearly easier to
understand:

\begin{consolethree}[escapeinside=||]
x += 5;
y = x;
\end{consolethree}

Note that the \textit{+=} when called twice:

\begin{consolethree}[escapeinside=||]
(x += 5) += 5;
\end{consolethree}

operates on the same \textit{x}. This means that \textit{+=}, besides
incrementing \textit{x}, also returns a reference to x so that the second
\textit{+=} operators on the same \textit{x}. If \textit{+=} returns a new
\textit{int} value that has the same value as \textit{x} after incrementing,
then the second \textit{+=} would have operated on this new \textit{int}
value and not on \textit{x}. Therefore the right thing to do is to return
a reference to \textit{x} and not a copy of \textit{x}.

Of course returning a reference is faster than returning an object since
objects tend to consume more memory. References are implemented using
pointers and pointers take up very little memory.

Refer to the \textit{Date} example. Suppose the \textit{add\_y} method is to
add an integer value to the year value, \textit{and} return the value of
the object.

\begin{consolethree}[escapeinside=||]
// Date.h
...
class Date
{
public:
    ...
    Date & add_y(int);
    ...
private:
    int yyyy_, mm_, dd_;
};
...
\end{consolethree}

\begin{consolethree}[escapeinside=||]
// Date.cpp
...
Date & Date::add_y(int inc)
{
    yyyy_ += inc;
    return *this;
}
...
\end{consolethree}

With the above, I can now do this:

\begin{consolethree}[escapeinside=||]
Date today(1, 1, 1970);
today.add_y(1).add_y(3);
\end{consolethree}

The first invocation of \textit{add\_y} will add 1 to the year of
\textit{today} and then a reference to \textit{today} is returned. Therefore
the second \textit{add\_y} is called by this reference, which means that
the second \textit{add\_y} is called by \textit{today}.

However if you do this:

\begin{consolethree}[escapeinside=||]
// Date.cpp
...
Date Date::add_y(int inc)
{
    y += inc;
    return *this;
}
...
\end{consolethree}

i.e., return a \textit{Date} object instead of a reference, then
\textit{Date}'s copy constructor is used to create a new
\textit{Date} object from \textit{*this}. This object is returned to
\textit{main()} and the \textit{add\_y} is called by this object so that
\textit{today} does not have its year incremented by 3.

We now look at returning references from a function call or method call.
There's nothing new here about references.

