\newpage\EMPHASIZE{Returning reference to member variable}

Of course you can also return a reference to a member (yes I know
I've already talked about this before).

\begin{consolethree}[escapeinside=||]
class Point2d
{
public:
    int & get_x()
    {
        return x_;
    }
    void print()
    {
        std::cout << x_ << ',' << y_ << '\n';
    }
private:
    int x_, y_;
};

int main()
{
    Point2d p;
    p.print();
    int & a = p.get_x();
    a = 0;
    p.print();
    return 0;
}
\end{consolethree}

But remember about information hiding. Clients usually should not have
direct access to instance variables. The class (and the objects) should
provide services to clients through methods and hide internal
implementation from outsiders. This makes the software more
maintainable.

And you definitely cannot do this in a method:

\begin{consolethree}[escapeinside=||]
class Point2d
{
public:
    int & get_x()
    {
        int x = x_;
        return x; // ERROR! Returning reference to
                  // local variable!!! Arghh!!!
    }
private:
    int x_, y_;
};
\end{consolethree}


\newpage\EMPHASIZE{Temporary object values}

Most of the time we have objects with names:

\begin{consolethree}[escapeinside=||]
Date date(1970, 1, 1);
date.print();
\end{consolethree}

Of course you can create object values not bound to names:

\begin{consolethree}[escapeinside=||]
Date(1970, 1, 1).print();
\end{consolethree}

(I've already talked about this.)

In the second case above, we have a temporary object, or an object value
that does not belong to an object name.

In the \textit{Int} class, if you have operator+ returns object values,
you might see temporary objects:

\begin{consolethree}[escapeinside=||]
Int i(5), j(7), k (8);
Int z = i + j + k; // i + j is temporary object
                   // this temporary object is
                   // added with k to produce
                   // another temporary object
\end{consolethree}

Of course, just like a method, a function can return an object value

\begin{consolethree}[escapeinside=||]
Date rand_date()
{
    return Date(rand()%10 + 1,
                rand()%10 + 1, rand());
}
\end{consolethree}

Of course this is different from returning a reference:

\begin{consolethree}[escapeinside=||]
Date & Date::f()
{
    return (*this);
}

int main()
{
    Date date(1, 1, 1970);
    date.f(); // A reference to date
              // is returned
}
\end{consolethree}

A temporary object can be destroyed immediately after the expression
containing the temporary object is computed.

There is an exception ... you can create an object name and bind it
to a temporary object value. In this case the temporary object value is
not destroyed immediately. For instance

\begin{consolethree}[escapeinside=||]
int main()
{
    Date date1 = rand_date();
    ...
}
\end{consolethree}

The value of \textit{date1} is actually the same as the value of the
object returned by \textit{rand\_date()}, i.e., there is no copy
constructor call. To verify this add some print statements:

\begin{consolethree}[escapeinside=||]
Date randdate()
{
    Date ret(rand() % 10 + 1,
             rand() % 10 + 1, rand());
    std::cout << &ret << '\n';
    return ret;
}

int main()
{
    Date date1 = f();
    std::cout << &date1 << '\n';
}
\end{consolethree}

You can also insert print statements in the \textit{Date} destructor to
verify that there is only one destructor call, not two, i.e., in the
above, there is really only one \textit{Date} value.

\begin{consolethree}[escapeinside=||]
rand_date(); // Date value returned by
             // rand_date() is not bound to a
             // name. It's destroyed.
             // Destructor is called.

Date date1 = rand_date(); // Date value bound to
                          // date1. Destructor not
                          // called yet
\end{consolethree}

In the above example:

\begin{consolethree}[escapeinside=||]
Date date1 = rand_date();
\end{consolethree}

the destructor is called only when the name \textit{date1} goes out of
scope.

Here are the scenarios you should study and be familiar with:

\begin{consolethree}[escapeinside=||]
Date Date::f(...) { ...; return *this; }
Date & Date::f(...) { ...; return *this; }
Date Date::f(...) { ...; Date x; return x; }
Date & Date::f(...) { ...; Date x; return x; } (error)
Date Date::f(...) { ...; return Date(1,1,1970); }
Date & Date::f(...) { ...; return Date(1,1,1970); } (error)
(date1.f()).print()
Date date2 = date1.f()
Date & date2 = date1.f()
\end{consolethree}


\newpage\EMPHASIZE{Avoid similar names}

\begin{consolethree}[escapeinside=||]
int x_ = 0;

int m2()
{
    return 5;
}

class C
{
public:
    void m1()
    {
        x_ = m2();
    }
    void m2()
    {
        return 0;
    }
private:
    int x_;
};
\end{consolethree}

Avoid such ambiguities! What's this about ...

\begin{consolethree}[escapeinside=||]
class C
{
public:
    void m(int x_)
    {
        std::cout << x_;
    }
private:
    int x_;
};
\end{consolethree}

In general here's how C++ search for names in the above
cases: first local variables are searched, then instance variables
(member variables), and then globals.


\newpage\EMPHASIZE{Notes}

In some programming languages, instead of \textit{this} (in a method)
which points to the object invoking the method, in other programming
languages there's a \textit{self} or \textit{me} in a method
this plays the same role as \textit{this} except that it is a reference to
the object invoking the method.


\newpage\EMPHASIZE{Forcing a reference parameter to be constant}

Recall: When writing a function, it's a good idea to use \textit{const}
for arguments that should not be changed. This is the case for both
(regular) functions and methods of a class:

\begin{consolethree}[escapeinside=||]
// function
void f(const C & c) { ... }

// method in class C
void C::g(const C & c) { ... }
\end{consolethree}

The following example shows 4 possible ways of pass-by-reference:

\begin{itemize}
\item Non-const to non-const \&
\item Non-const to const \&
\item Const to non-const \&
\item Const to const \&
\end{itemize}

Which ones work and which do not? Here's an experiment
that will help.

\begin{consolethree}[escapeinside=||]
void f(const int & i) {}
void g(int & i) {}

int main()
{
    int i = 0;
    const int j = 0;
    f(i); // nonconst passed to const reference
    f(j); // const passed to const reference
    g(i); // nonconst passed to nonconst reference
    g(j); // const passed to nonconst reference
    return 0;
}
\end{consolethree}

First figure out on your own which is reasonable. Compile this and read
the error message. Correct and check by compiling the program.

Answer:

\begin{itemize}
\item Non-const to non-const \& OK
\item Non-const to const \& OK
\item Const to non-const \& BAD!!!
\item Const to const \& OK
\end{itemize}

Why?

\begin{consolethree}[escapeinside=||]
void g(int & i) {} // i not constant
                   // g() can change i

int main()
{
    const int j = 0; // j cannot be changed
    g(j); // oops ... now what?
}
\end{consolethree}

The case of object parameters is the same.

The following example shows 4 possible ways of pass-by-reference:

\begin{itemize}
\item Non-const to non-const \&
\item Non-const to const \&
\item Const to non-const \&
\item Const to const \&
\end{itemize}

Which ones work and which do not?

\begin{consolethree}[escapeinside=||]
class C {};

void f(const C & y) {}
void g(C & y) {}

int main()
{
    C a;
    const C b = C();
    f(a);
    f(b);
    g(a);
    g(b);
    return 0;
}
\end{consolethree}

Answer:

\begin{itemize}
\item Non-const to non-const \& OK
\item Non-const to const \& OK
\item Const to non-const \& BAD!!!
\item Const to const \& OK
\end{itemize}

Why?

\begin{consolethree}[escapeinside=||]
class C{};

void h(C & x) {} // h can modify x

int main()
{
    const C y = C(); // y cannot be modified
    h(y); // oops ... now what???
}
\end{consolethree}

In summary if \textit{T} is any type (\textit{int}, \textit{char}, ...,
some \textit{class}, ...), and \textit{f()} has the following prototype:

\textit{void f(\textbf{T \& x});}

and y is a \textbf{\textit{constant}} \textit{T} object, then the following
is incorrect:

\begin{consolethree}[escapeinside=||]
const T y;
f(y);
\end{consolethree}

