\newpage\EMPHASIZE{Summary}

\begin{itemize}
\item When an object \textit{obj} invokes a method \textit{m}, a pointer called
  \textit{this} is in the scope of \textit{m}. The \textit{this} pointer
  points to \textit{obj}. In other words, in a method, the \textit{this}
  pointer always point to the object invoking the method. (See section
  on static methods for exception.)

\item In the body of a method, if an object \textit{obj} has instance variable
  \textit{x\_}, then the following are the same:

\textit{x\_} is the same as \textit{this->x\_}

\item In the body of a method, if an object \textit{obj} has another method
  called \textit{m}, then the following are the same:

\textit{m()} is the same as \textit{this->m()}

\item A method can return a copy of the value of the object of class
  \textit{C}:

\begin{consolethree}[escapeinside=||]
C C::m()
{
    ...
    return *this;
}
\end{consolethree}

\item or a reference to itself:

\begin{consolethree}[escapeinside=||]
C & C::m()
{
    ...
    return *this;
}
\end{consolethree}

\item If a method returns a reference to itself, then you can chain up
  methods:

\textit{obj.m().m1()}

  where \textit{m1} is another method and \textit{m1} is also invoked by
  \textit{obj}.

\item WARNING: If \textit{m} does not return a reference of the invoking
  object, then in the following:

\textit{obj.m().m1()}

  \textit{m1()} is not invoked by \textit{obj}, but rather by a copy of
  \textit{obj}.

\item A constant method is a method that cannot modify the object invoking
  the method.

\item A method is made constant by putting the word \textit{const} on the
  right of the method header. This is done in the header file and if the
  method is defined outside the class definition, then it must also be
  done in the definition of the method.
\end{itemize}

